try to give it to you in a way so that you can take this to your next marketing project.

00:01:15.839 --> 00:01:19.360
Talk a little bit about what good survey design is, or what I think it is.

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:23.360
There's an interesting bit of intellectual property that the

00:01:25.040 --> 00:01:30.400
ability to work on called customer quotient, similar in a way to NPS, but also very different.

00:01:31.199 --> 00:01:34.400
We'll look at some parameters to constraints, then getting involved in the machine learning

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:37.760
part of how do you actually do machine learning with survey data.

00:01:38.320 --> 00:01:43.199
So the role of this was, how do you take a survey, because that's what a lot of people

00:01:43.199 --> 00:01:48.959
in marketing research do, and develop a segmentation engine out of it, so that as people

00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:55.519
complete your survey, you can put them in the right segment for whatever, and your segments

00:01:55.519 --> 00:02:02.959
can be based on whatever. In this case, this was a sort of a behavioral psychographic

00:02:03.519 --> 00:02:09.199
segmentation, which means it wasn't so much, you bought product A, B, or you live in this

00:02:09.199 --> 00:02:15.199
part of the world, or wherever. This is more about how you feel and how you behave.

00:02:16.399 --> 00:02:21.119
And so it gives you a little different approach to sort of the different dimensions of marketing.

00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:27.839
And it was looking to reveal, this is, again, this is part of a much larger project,

00:02:27.919 --> 00:02:34.800
how people view companies. And the other way to think about it is, at the end of the day,

00:02:34.800 --> 00:02:42.080
it rates how customer-centric a company is. And that's how the questions were sort of phrased.

00:02:45.199 --> 00:02:48.080
So these are some of the things that I've learned about what makes a good survey.

00:02:48.080 --> 00:02:53.919
And these are just my, these are my takeaways from being involved in surveys and trying to

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:59.039
apply machine learning and, you know, how do you get it, how do you ensure you get a lot of

00:02:59.039 --> 00:03:04.479
respondents, et cetera. So the first thing is, I want a goal of, like, what is the survey design

00:03:04.479 --> 00:03:09.919
to answer? And then you're going to want to have some supporting questions. So I was thinking

00:03:09.919 --> 00:03:16.320
structurally, that's how we want to start it. And the goal, you shouldn't have more than three

00:03:16.320 --> 00:03:21.919
things you're trying to answer. I usually say one to two is good, just in case, you know,

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:28.000
you pick up some other ancillary information. And these goal statements are binaries, yes, no's.

00:03:29.279 --> 00:03:36.160
My first experience was dealing with a survey and people are like, well, how likely are you to

00:03:37.679 --> 00:03:41.039
purchase from us again? And so you end up with these neutral, you know,

00:03:41.039 --> 00:03:44.960
everybody's in the neutral range, and it doesn't really help you out. Or what do you do when

00:03:45.520 --> 00:03:53.759
you get a handful at the positive and a handful in the negative and a handful in the neutral?

00:03:53.759 --> 00:03:56.479
Do you drop them? Do you include them with something else? So this sort of resolves that

00:03:56.479 --> 00:04:04.800
issue. It's a simple yes, no. With that, the supporting questions, you want as few as you

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:09.919
can get away with, but still get the information that you want. So, you know, I like to think

00:04:09.919 --> 00:04:15.119
maybe you're between five and 10 questions. If you start getting over 10 questions,

00:04:16.079 --> 00:04:18.320
you're just getting too much, you're asking for too much information,

00:04:19.279 --> 00:04:26.399
and you'll find that people will drop out over time. The flip side around it is in the marketing

00:04:26.399 --> 00:04:31.519
research world, you do have the ability to pay people with, pick your incentive, Amazon gift

00:04:31.519 --> 00:04:36.880
card, PayPal, whatever else, they will stay in for longer, knowing that if they finish it, they'll

00:04:36.880 --> 00:04:43.359
get some money at the end. And I've done a couple of these, I've done many of both,

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:49.040
and there doesn't seem to be a difference in engagement as far as like, you get different

00:04:49.040 --> 00:04:57.760
answers if you pay people. And then here's a key thing. I like my supporting questions. So we got

00:04:57.760 --> 00:05:04.559
our one binary, like now instead of how likely are you to buy from me again, is I have bought

00:05:04.559 --> 00:05:09.839
from you again, or I will buy from you again, yes or no? And then we're going to ask a bunch

00:05:09.839 --> 00:05:14.399
of questions that support it. And I think everybody's seen these, strongly agree,

00:05:14.399 --> 00:05:22.799
agree, neutral, et cetera. I do not like that scale. One, you don't get as much variability

00:05:22.799 --> 00:05:29.200
in the modeling phase, whereas one to 10 gives you plenty of variability. And I think if you

00:05:29.200 --> 00:05:34.959
go over more than 10, people don't know what the numbers mean. And just as a little aside,

00:05:34.959 --> 00:05:39.519
I worked in the wine industry for a while, and you know, they have their 100 point wine scale.

00:05:39.519 --> 00:05:44.799
But the funny thing is 99 point, whatever percentage of the wines are ranked between

00:05:45.600 --> 00:05:50.880
80 and 100. So what they really have is a 20 point scale. And so I don't know, they disguise

00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:57.040
it as a 100 point scale versus 20 point scale. Same thing here. 10 points will give you enough

00:05:57.040 --> 00:06:03.200
variability. And then the other thing is, you know, people always say, oh, we can ask a question

00:06:03.200 --> 00:06:09.279
a different way to make sure that we don't have people gaming the system. Maybe if you get this

00:06:09.279 --> 00:06:14.239
giant survey that are like a personality test or something like that, but that's a whole different

00:06:14.239 --> 00:06:20.559
animal here. If you're surveying your customers, they're not going to, they're not going to do the

00:06:20.559 --> 00:06:24.079
duplicates. And if they start seeing the duplicates, it'd be like, this is a waste of time.

00:06:24.079 --> 00:06:28.239
And it's also a waste of your time, too. Like every question matters.

00:06:29.839 --> 00:06:33.440
And I've seen some other indices out there where they have like,

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:40.880
they try to decompose like a net promoter score, which into three indices, and it's kind of like,

00:06:42.079 --> 00:06:46.480
the three indices are so incredibly correlated that you just wasted two questions

00:06:47.440 --> 00:06:52.399
asking about the other two indices when they're like 90% correlated. So it's kind of like,

00:06:52.399 --> 00:06:58.000
you really have one index. In the market world, I know anybody who's worked in marketing has heard

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:03.760
of net promoter score. It's kind of a hybrid because it does ask on a scale of one to 10.

00:07:03.760 --> 00:07:07.519
But you can also, but at the end of the day, you can make people binaries out of it. In fact,

00:07:07.519 --> 00:07:15.440
there is a, you know, people that score you nine and 10 are your promoters,

00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:24.000
six to eight are your neutrals, and five and below are your detractors. And the score only

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:29.920
works with promoters and detractors. So it's a very unique scale. But when you do NPS,

00:07:29.920 --> 00:07:36.399
you should really ask, you know, get into the whys. And then a good rule of thumb is to try to

00:07:36.399 --> 00:07:41.200
get about 1000 responses. Because you can do some really good modeling. I know everybody thinks,

00:07:41.440 --> 00:07:45.040
this is a world of big data, I need 10,000, I need 100,000, I need a million. No, you don't.

00:07:46.239 --> 00:07:51.519
You need a well designed survey. And if you get close to 1000 responses, you will get

00:07:51.519 --> 00:07:59.200
a reasonable amount of information. What's interesting about surveys, is that if your

00:07:59.200 --> 00:08:04.880
questions are distinctive enough, then even if you get smaller segments, you will be able to predict

00:08:04.880 --> 00:08:11.440
them. So for instance, you know, if segment one is questions one to three, and you know,

00:08:11.440 --> 00:08:16.640
segment two is maybe a question three and question four, but then segment three is this oddball

00:08:16.640 --> 00:08:21.440
question, question five, even if it comes out small, and you get into this highly imbalanced

00:08:23.200 --> 00:08:27.359
data scenario, the fact that question five is so unique, it will help

00:08:28.239 --> 00:08:32.719
even with the prediction in an imbalanced situation, because it's not random.

00:08:35.520 --> 00:08:40.320
So a little bit about customer quotient. This is developed by a colleague of mine at C Space in

00:08:40.320 --> 00:08:47.039
Boston, Dr. Manel Austin. And it talks and it builds on this cost of this sort of how

00:08:48.159 --> 00:08:53.440
customer centric as your company, and they ask questions from from the customer's perspective,

00:08:53.440 --> 00:08:58.080
and you build up the pyramid from, you know, relevance, you're just in the game at that point.

00:08:59.280 --> 00:09:02.239
Then we have a customer series of questions around customer experience,

00:09:02.559 --> 00:09:09.200
how well you do, then the better you are, you get into openness, and that begins to really unlock

00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:16.559
the doors. Are you willing to have an honest and open two way dialogue with your customers?

00:09:18.559 --> 00:09:26.559
Empathy is really what changes the game. So when I've seen companies in the segments,

00:09:27.280 --> 00:09:33.520
companies in the segments, it's not till you do reasonably well at the openness,

00:09:33.520 --> 00:09:38.960
and get into empathy that you begin to really like, we've grouped different companies and

00:09:38.960 --> 00:09:42.799
segments and everything else. And you see, when you start rating up on the empathy scores,

00:09:42.799 --> 00:09:47.840
you begin to run away, and become extremely well. And the last one is what we call emotional

00:09:47.840 --> 00:09:52.640
validation. Those are the people out there that are selling your product on their recommendations.

00:09:53.200 --> 00:09:57.760
What we used to talk about is you have two people, you have three people having a conversation,

00:09:57.760 --> 00:10:02.719
someone says, I need to get a new smartphone. And the first person says, get an iPhone phone,

00:10:02.719 --> 00:10:06.960
and the other person really doesn't say anything. So your iPhone is your sort of emotional validation

00:10:06.960 --> 00:10:10.719
person. And they'll give you five reasons why you should get an iPhone. Or on the flip side,

00:10:10.719 --> 00:10:14.960
they'll give you five reasons why you should get an Android or whatever it is, but they are selling

00:10:14.960 --> 00:10:22.080
your product. And it's called emotional validation. Those are your ultimate customers, because they

00:10:22.080 --> 00:10:26.960
are doing your marketing. And we find that people that score higher up there actually have to spend

00:10:26.960 --> 00:10:31.440
less in marketing and advertisement over the long term, and they get some better scores.

00:10:31.440 --> 00:10:35.919
That's just a little bit of this intellectual property area in the space that I worked on here.

00:10:38.479 --> 00:10:43.520
For those with traditional marketing backgrounds, where you talk about the four P's and the three

00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:51.119
C's and all those. So the four P's, product price, place and promotion. The three C's are customer,

00:10:51.119 --> 00:10:58.559
company and competition. And what these do is sort of map various questions that help with the

00:11:00.320 --> 00:11:08.159
CQ scoring into these different traditional marketing buckets. So that when we talked

00:11:08.159 --> 00:11:12.799
about pitching this to different companies, if I had a traditional marketer, I could say, yeah,

00:11:12.799 --> 00:11:20.479
this is your product piece, this is your price piece. And you can see price, it's all from that

00:11:20.479 --> 00:11:25.599
customer point of view. The company appreciates my loyalty. And that's literally how the question

00:11:25.599 --> 00:11:33.599
worked. It's an action word, or I don't feel ripped off. And you can see in most of these

00:11:33.599 --> 00:11:40.559
questions, and these are sort of paraphrases of it, but we've made it action oriented, and it's

00:11:40.559 --> 00:11:46.640
from the customer standpoint, not I. Versus if you think about a lot of surveys is the company is

00:11:46.640 --> 00:11:52.640
asking, do you like us? Do we do a good job at this and things like that? Whereas

00:11:53.520 --> 00:11:56.400
this whole framework really reverses it around.

00:12:00.960 --> 00:12:06.479
So let's talk about this project that we had. Client specification number one had to be built

