a web app. But at the same time, it's workable. What it does do is it changes the model

00:12:23.280 --> 00:12:26.719
processing a little bit. I'm not going to be able to run XGBoost or any of that.

00:12:27.760 --> 00:12:31.599
But at the same time, I may not need to. And there's a good way that I get around this

00:12:31.599 --> 00:12:40.799
down the road. Our sample size was 900, not 1,000. But that's fine. And it's like, okay,

00:12:41.760 --> 00:12:44.799
we're probably only going to get about three or four segments out of this.

00:12:46.080 --> 00:12:55.840
And part of this came out of is that a major company had a project with a major consulting

00:12:55.840 --> 00:13:00.479
company. And they said, well, you have eight distinctive segments. And it was like, okay,

00:13:00.479 --> 00:13:05.200
really? So we're going to test out whether we really have eight distinctive behaviors

00:13:06.159 --> 00:13:14.000
by using this survey. And the initial step, and this is one of the things that, like I said,

00:13:15.440 --> 00:13:22.320
this one did not have the dependent variable. And that's why I added it in early on as a good

00:13:22.320 --> 00:13:29.200
survey has a binary outcome. So we had to create one or create some sort of segmentation outcome.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:34.080
The nice thing is survey questions on a 1 to 10 scale, easy to work with.

00:13:35.599 --> 00:13:39.599
And if you think about it, from the machine learning world, as we go down the road,

00:13:41.520 --> 00:13:45.280
we're not going to have to center scale or do any of that with the data. It's already

00:13:45.280 --> 00:13:56.239
prepackaged on a 1 to 10 scale. And we're good. Whether we do any kind of, and we're going to do

00:13:56.239 --> 00:14:01.520
unsupervised learning or supervised, you are not going to have to rescale all the data, which

00:14:02.640 --> 00:14:09.919
makes it nice. And when you do some of these things, and these end ones are my discussion

00:14:09.919 --> 00:14:20.960
with them, what's good enough actors? Are there penalties for false positives or false negatives?

00:14:20.960 --> 00:14:25.760
Like if we put the person in the wrong segment, how costly is it to your business?

00:14:26.479 --> 00:14:34.159
And should we add penalties if they are costly in one way or another?

00:14:36.559 --> 00:14:41.200
And that would change a little bit of the modeling too. We would actually add a cost

00:14:42.239 --> 00:14:47.359
matrix into it down the road if we had to. But in this case, there weren't too many big deals.

00:14:47.359 --> 00:14:52.320
And they said, you know what? You give me 80% of the way, you give me 80% of the right answers,

00:14:52.960 --> 00:14:58.479
I'll be happy. I was like, okay, 85, that's what we're shooting for. Hopefully we can do better.

00:14:58.479 --> 00:15:02.479
That's one of the things for me is I always like to be in the 90s.

00:15:04.559 --> 00:15:07.840
But sometimes it doesn't always work out that way.

00:15:10.799 --> 00:15:13.359
So here's a little roadmap here. And you can use this

00:15:14.239 --> 00:15:19.679
over and over, like any kind of survey work you do. I've used this format

00:15:20.640 --> 00:15:25.760
for a lot of NPS modeling that I've done for various companies over time.

00:15:27.840 --> 00:15:32.799
Design a nice survey. So we ask for NPS people, we ask that question, but then we ask them

00:15:32.799 --> 00:15:37.919
questions about customer service, we ask them questions about pricing, other aspects of the

00:15:37.919 --> 00:15:44.000
business to see what you're trying to do is figure out what drives that answer, what drives that yes,

00:15:44.559 --> 00:15:51.840
no. So then we're going to do some clustering, I like hierarchical clustering, it's easy for

00:15:51.840 --> 00:15:58.559
visualization, the scale is easy. So we're going to separate our respondents into some

00:15:59.119 --> 00:16:04.159
different segments and clusters. And then we're going to create a dummy variable for each one.

00:16:04.159 --> 00:16:09.440
So you're in segment one or you're not, you're in segment two, you're not, you're in segment three,

00:16:09.440 --> 00:16:15.679
you're not. I think a lot of people would try to go straight to sort of a multinomial model,

00:16:15.679 --> 00:16:19.200
hey, we're just going to predict what segment you're in right out of with one equation.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:23.599
Those require a lot of data. So yeah, if you're in one of these big data worlds,

00:16:23.599 --> 00:16:30.799
and you've got 10,000s or 50,000, you could probably pull it off with 1000 simple

00:16:30.799 --> 00:16:34.960
binaries is going to be the way to go. So here's my little my little magic here.

00:16:35.760 --> 00:16:38.400
What I first do is use the elastic net regression,

00:16:39.280 --> 00:16:43.520
the glimnet model, a glimnet package by Trevor Hassey, Rob Tertranian.

00:16:45.599 --> 00:16:50.719
It was designed for genomics, it really will help you reduce dimensionality,

00:16:51.919 --> 00:16:57.520
and it's extremely fast. And to give you a little bit more information on this,

00:16:57.760 --> 00:17:07.359
um, the people that are familiar with ridge, or lasso regression, this is the hybrid. So a ridge

00:17:07.359 --> 00:17:15.920
will attempt to squeeze down all your coefficients to make them very small. And the lasso will do is

00:17:15.920 --> 00:17:20.640
if there are multiple variables that are correlated, the lasso will pick one and leave the

00:17:20.640 --> 00:17:25.520
other ones out. Now the problem with lasso regression is you don't know why it made the

00:17:25.520 --> 00:17:32.959
decision. Is it, you know, a function of the gradient descent, or a function of the order

00:17:32.959 --> 00:17:39.040
of the data, you just don't know. And they talk about it in their paper about that, whereas what

00:17:39.040 --> 00:17:44.959
the elastic net does is, I have three variables that are correlated. If they're statistically

00:17:44.959 --> 00:17:50.000
valid, we leave them all, we leave all three in, if they're not statistically valid, we pull them

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:58.719
all out. And so that's why, how it gets to your dimensionality reduction. So then this last step

00:17:58.719 --> 00:18:04.319
is, all right, we got to go into Excel. Now you probably could do an elastic net, maybe not,

00:18:04.880 --> 00:18:09.199
in Excel, but you can easily do a logistic regression. And so what we're going to do is

00:18:10.239 --> 00:18:15.680
build out our template. So when we get batches of scores, we just run them through our

00:18:16.560 --> 00:18:19.680
worksheet with logistic regression in there,

00:18:20.319 --> 00:18:25.920
and then it's going to use a voting method, and it'll choose which segment you're in.

00:18:29.280 --> 00:18:35.920
So the first thing we did is, we run this, the elbow, famous elbow plot used for clustering.

00:18:35.920 --> 00:18:41.760
And it's called within the sum of the squares residuals. And so what we got is number of

00:18:41.760 --> 00:18:46.239
clusters, they told me they had eight segments, so I went for up to eight clusters, or at least

00:18:46.239 --> 00:18:51.199
their consulting company did. And what we're looking for is the bend in the plot. And you can

00:18:51.199 --> 00:18:57.199
see, you get the elbow at about three or four, at which point then it all sort of flattens out. So

00:18:59.199 --> 00:19:03.199
if I had a lot more data, I probably would shoot for four clusters.

00:19:04.079 --> 00:19:11.439
Given that it was only 900 respondents, three would probably do the job. You can see that

00:19:12.239 --> 00:19:18.160
the sum of the squares goes down, obviously, the most between one, two, and three,

00:19:18.160 --> 00:19:21.760
between three and four, it's very little enough that tails off. So that's why we're looking at that

00:19:23.040 --> 00:19:29.439
inflection point. So we plot them all out visually, we get three groups.

00:19:30.239 --> 00:19:35.359
And this isn't, you know, you can see in the hierarchical clustering,

00:19:38.079 --> 00:19:43.199
that you get the divisions, almost fairly cleanly between the blue block and the green block,

00:19:45.199 --> 00:19:48.239
and the green block and the red block. And the other way to interpret this is,

00:19:49.119 --> 00:19:55.680
the people in the blue block are very different from the people in the red segment.

00:19:56.640 --> 00:20:03.520
And there's some gradations across the middle. I use this plot a lot when I do

00:20:05.119 --> 00:20:10.239
text analytics, because it's really fun then. Because what you're seeing is, when you do this

00:20:10.239 --> 00:20:14.800
with text, is these people are saying one thing, they're saying something similar to these guys.

00:20:16.079 --> 00:20:18.959
But now it's getting different, and then you get something really weird at the other end.

00:20:19.119 --> 00:20:30.319
So I like this plot from a visual standpoint. And the other axis is just the distance metric.

00:20:32.319 --> 00:20:35.920
And as I mentioned, because all of our questions were a one to 10 scale,

00:20:37.359 --> 00:20:43.839
I didn't have to rescale anything to be able to do this clustering. And yep, this is small,

00:20:44.640 --> 00:20:48.640
and it may be difficult to predict, but it doesn't automatically mean that. Because as I said,

00:20:48.640 --> 00:20:53.599
if there are certain questions that are answered by a handful of people in the group, that makes

00:20:53.599 --> 00:20:58.479
them marketably different, then you'll still be pretty good at predicting whether or not people

00:20:58.479 --> 00:21:09.680
